Reference vs Pointer

Reference: A reference is an alias for an existing variable. 
It is used as if it were the original variable, without any special syntax.

A reference is a dereferenced pointer.

std::string& loginRef = bob.getLoginRef();
loginRef = "newLogin";  // Directly modifies _login

Pointer: A pointer holds the memory address of a variable. 
You need to use the dereference operator * to access or modify the value.

We use pointers when we need a variable out of our scope. Allocate on heap, not on stack.

std::string* loginPtr = bob.getLoginPtr();
*loginPtr = "newLogin";  // Dereference to modify _login

Initialization:
-------------
Reference: Must be initialized at the time of declaration and cannot be changed to reference another variable later.

Pointer: Can be initialized to nullptr and can point to different variables at different times.

Memory Address:
------------------

Reference: Automatically dereferenced, so you don't directly see the address manipulation. 
You can't get the address of a reference itself, but you can get the address of the variable it refers to.

Pointer: Stores the memory address of the variable, and you can manipulate the address directly.

Nullability:
-----------
Reference: Cannot be null. It must always refer to a valid object.

Pointer: Can be null, which means it can point to nothing.
